From summary we can see that Adjusted R-sqr is very low. In addition, with checkresidual acf we can see that there are corelation information still left in the residual. Residual is a normal distribution. This model does not capture all the information.

## [1,] -16175.14 -10159.29 -4142.893 7889.993

The model has some significant autocorrelation in the residuals, which means the prediction intervals may not provide accurate coverage.

Also, the histogram of the residuals shows one negative outlier, which will also affect the coverage of the prediction intervals.

Residuals<-cbind("1-1-0"=tsreg.sarima1$residuals,"1-1-0.5"=tsreg.sarima2$residuals,"1-1-1"=tsreg.sarima3$residuals,"1-1-2"=tsreg.sarima4$residuals)

m.var<-VAR(tsreg.train[,c(1:6)],p=10,type = "both",season = 12)
#summary(m.var)
serial.test(m.var, lags.pt = 10, type = "PT.asymptotic")
## 
##  Portmanteau Test (asymptotic)
## 
## data:  Residuals of VAR object m.var
## Chi-squared = 61.83, df = 0, p-value < 2.2e-16
acf(residuals(m.var))

fcast.m.var<-forecast(m.var,h=48)
plot(fcast.m.var)
